,Recommended,263820,9353805,"Posted: 5 March, 2014",all,Cliff,"I recommend this game, mainly because of the price. If not for that, it wouldn't be worth owning. EvilQuest, is not the kind of game that is fresh, or new. Many of the retro styled games at least try to advance on old ideas; whereas this one is a blatant copy of one of my favorite titles, Crystalis. The charging of your weapon, to the layout of the overworld. There is however a refreshing feeling I have, when playing it. It may be a copy, but it is done quite well. Sure, one could argue, that the sprite design is poor, and cheesily bad. But then again look at LJN; they were charging full game price, and most of their games were hardly playable. One area 'EvilQuest' tries to advance, is the story. Now, back in the old times of NES, and SNES, we were always forced to play as the 'Hero'. This was the way things were; and it worked, damn well, at that. This was the golden age; the stories were good, the gameplay was majorly addicting, and the sprites were done so well, that we could literally see them pop off the screen. Evilquest does some of these things right. But I digress. The story is one area where they advanced, as we get to play as the villian, for once. You start out as a reknowned antagonist named, Galvis. He is all sorts of evil badassery. We are only told this through the title, game trailer, and some of the dialogue. Thus, it is the weakest point in the game. When all you are killing is monsters in the overworld; how can you call your game, EvilQuest? Seriously, this is my only real annoyance. 6/10 Great price, somewhat good title."
76561198090514931,Recommended,263820,9366947,"Posted: 6 March, 2014",all,emaildlk,"The game is an awesome throwback to old SNES games I grew up on. Also, I immediately thought of the classic NES game Crystalis because there are so many similiaries. For $2 you cannot go wrong on this game. I love that there are so many indie developers paying homage to the golden age of gaming and this is one that is up there for a must play for anyone who grew up with NES and/or SNES. I art is very amatuerish but do not let that fool you this game is about gameplay. The game does seem very derivative and it seems to get really repetitive the thing that saves it the most is the fact that you are the villian instead of the hero which turns the old school action RPG on its head. Our ""hero"" is on a mission to conquer and pillage and burn everything good. The story is very similar to other games of its ilk that require you to go through different dungeons and find important items so you can move to the next area. Certain items are required to advance the game and things need to be done in a certain order. There is no objective marker telling you exactly where to go and who to talk to. So discovery is an important aspect of the game just like in the classic 16-bit Action RPGs. There is no excuse to pass up this gem at only a measly $2."
