76561197977398448,Recommended,263820,17377120,"Posted: 3 August, 2015",all,AshBurnem,"I was ahugefan of Crystalis on the NES. I still own the cartridge, in fact. For decades I have wanted more of that game, be it a sequel or, as is the case in EvilQuest, a 'spiritual successor'. A mere two hours in, I feel confident in saying that this game delivers.EvilQuest takes Crystalis and ever-so-slightly modernizes it, like adding in a map, quest log, improving the menu functions, and allowing the player to customize the character when levelling up. What it doesnotdo is add in unnecessary filters, particle effects, and bloom that would've been impossible in, say, 1990. It feels exactly like an early SNES or very late NES game, and is clearly made by a developer who loved his game.I have some slight disappointment in that there are no sort of puzzles in this game, just 'Do you have the McGuffin?"" anti-sequence-breaking checkpoints; this was one of my few complaints against Crystalis as well. You wander through the world murdering everything that you can, scouring the land for all the plot coupons to unlock the next zones. Thankfully,thisgame is kind enough to shepherd you back towards a relevant area so you don't spend hours looking through irrelevant low-level areas for things you've missed. The art style in the cutscenes also leaves something to be desired, but certainly falls within acceptable tolerances for an indie developer.Even with its limitations in mind, EvilQuest only costs a pittance, so if you enjoy top-down action RPGs you should certainly give this game a try."
